# Cerberus rule corpus + example credential values — detection patterns by definition.
#
# Files under cerberus/rules/ (and a few engine test fixtures) contain
# secret-shaped strings used as detection examples — the YARA-lite rules and
# YAML signatures look for these patterns in scanned skills, and the
# threat-analysis prompts illustrate what a malicious skill's hardcoded keys
# look like. They are NOT real credentials (Gate 2 git-history scan, 2026-06-09).
#
# NOTE: gitleaks `.gitleaksignore` accepts COMMIT FINGERPRINTS only — a path
# glob like `cerberus/rules/**` is silently rejected (it logged an "Invalid
# .gitleaksignore entry" warning and suppressed nothing). The actual
# suppression now lives in `.gitleaks.toml` `[allowlist]`, matched by literal
# value (not by path) so a genuine secret in these same files would still be
# flagged. See `.gitleaks.toml` for the allowlisted values and rationale.
#
# Cisco's upstream cisco-ai-defense/skill-scanner (SHA ff708ea, 2026-06-05)
# uses a path-based exclusion for its rule corpus; Charon uses value-based
# allowlisting instead — safer for a public repo. See cerberus/README.md + NOTICE.
